        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-04-04T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-04-04T08:00:00-05:00" n="137" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d137">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4–448: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-04-04T21:00:00+08:00">April 4, 1948—9 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 4—11:24 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>768. Chang Kia-ngau<note n="77" xml:id="d137fn77">Governor of the Central Bank of
                        China.</note> informs me: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Chiang Kai-shek is today informing Kmt that he will not accept
                            Presidency and recommends election of Hu Shih.<note n="78" xml:id="d137fn78">Chancellor of National Peking University.</note>
                        </item>
                        <pb facs="0192" n="182" xml:id="pg_182"/>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Generalissimo has done this: (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) to justify his
                            long stay in Ruling; (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) to get military to fight
                            war, not scramble for office.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>He thinks Generalissimo is not making mere gesture, but Kmt may force
                            Generalissimo to accept Presidency.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>He is sure Hu Shih will not accept and believes Generalissimo will
                            then support some elder statesman he can control.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>He is moderately optimistic impact of this development plus American
                            aid on Chinese public opinion.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Sent Department, repeated Nanking as 546.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cabot</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
